            "text": "\nIf I recall correctly, I made sure to define precisely what an OS was. An OS is a complete programmatic base. That means, whatever some programmer is going to see and use, that's the OS. And the innards of the OS are not the OS because the programmer doesn't see them. To prove that a particular scheduling algorithm is part of the OS, you need to demonstrate that the particular behaviour it engenders is not only perceptible but significant to programmers who use the OS. Something isn't part of an OS by the mere fact of being contained within it anymore than the undigested food I just ate is part of my body (or viruses, or bacteria).",
            "id": "a35881f80a94ce6dc12796dd4a4d530a"
